</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hobbess007>Hobbess007</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 5:19:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  another part of the theorem</span><hr size=1> Another thought occured to me on determining pet aggro.<br>
<br>
Someone once told me (though I never really took the time to look closely) that the second pet to be placed on a mob will usually take the aggro.<br>
<br>
I doubt this is wholly correct, but he seemed to beleive it fairly firmly, so I wonder if it dosen't have to do with the mechanics of a typical 2 pet situation, particularly with the beastlord proc spirit of the wind which has a knock back.<br>
<br>
It's been mentioned that the closer a melee is to a mob, the more aggro it generates, well if through bash/procs the first pet (P1) on a mob pushes the monster back, it would be pushing it closer to the pet attacking from the rear (P2).  Now P1 will move again to close to maximum melee range to the mob, but P2 will likely NOT move again as it is likely still in melee range, and is likely actually closer to the mob.  So now P2 has been attacking from the rear and dealing more damage because it is not getting blocked, and is closer to the mob.  This could in turn create enough aggro for the mob to change targets from P1 who engaged it first to P2.  And since normal (trinity) group logic would imply trying to have P1 who engages the mob first be the stronger pet, with the understanding that it should build some self aggro first before the others.  P1 being a tougher pet is likey to have more push to it than the pets in the rear, and will push the mob closer to them and send the aggro onto the weaker pets.<br>
<br>
That's just one more theory, but I think it warrants some investigation as one possibility.<br>
<br>
-Hobbess<br>
