</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2434<br> <font color=#333333>(12/3/02 5:59:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8009.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  So what are the real rules on hate?</span><hr size=1> Determining who gets aggro is clearly not simple.  Based on my experience and what I read here and elsewhere, I think we can give a number of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;rules of thumb&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that more or less apply:<br>
<br>
Players take aggro much more easily than pets.<br>
Being an easier target, e.g. lower level, fewer hitpoints, lower AC, etc., means more aggro.<br>
Frequent damage output, whether through melee or procs, generates more aggro.<br>
Closer targets are attacked more frequently.<br>
There appears to be some kind of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;pet hate pool&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> effect, where multiple pets make it easier for pets to take aggro over players.<br>
There are class hate modifiers, at least for monks, and possibly beastlords.<br>
Sensitivity to these rules can vary by mob or zone.<br>
<br>
What would be nice is to enumerate reliably the circumstances under which a player may melee beside pets, but have the pets take aggro.  This would allow us to open pet-centered groups to melees, which in turn would help mages teach others the value of mages and pets in groups.<br>
<br>
