<br>
We often pick up stragglers from the trinity castoffs who, like mages, have a hard time getting a group.  I have done several groups where the primary damage was pet-centric (mage, mage, BL, necro, cleric, druid - for example).  <br>
<br>
But I also constantly get statements like &quot;Wow, your pet really dishes the damage!&quot; in more traditional groups (indicating that these people are NOT familiar with what mages can do).  <br>
<br>
In a non-traditional grouping I often CC adds using my pet, often to the point of my pet killing the add before the primary target dies.  That 50 point DS is killer!<br>
<br>
I have seen some problems with high damage &quot;light tanks&quot;...  they easily take aggro off the epic pet, but do not have the hps or AC to tank very well.  The healer(cleric in my case) has to manage her mana much more closely, sometimes nuking to push the mob into run mode, instead of waiting for the rogue (as a common example) to do it.<br>
<br>
Regarding the PC aggro thing,  a couple of months ago, VI introduced an aspect of aggro based on HPs...  a certain amount of aggro is generated by the max HPs of PCs in melee.  The fewer HPs, the more aggro is generated.  I can let my pet tank a mob to under half life (without casting), step in to whack a bit to work on my 1hb (and do that uber 1 point of damage to get the xp)... and WHAM!  I have aggro.  I back out, and the pet takes over again.  Compare the HPs of the 50+ mage pets to non-plate PCs and it becomes quickly obvious that unless the PC is level 60 with lotsa gear, the pet has more hps by a lot.   Especially if it is buffed (cleric buffs add about 1100 hps, putitng my pet over the 5k mark).<br>
<br>
The net result is that the only PC that our pet can successfully taunt off of, is the only one we don't want them too... /grin. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub86.ezboard.com/bveterancrew"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.swbell.net/mkswet/ark_sig2.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
