<br>
Remember that Necromancers have a Undead Slow line (the Shackle line caps out at 70%), so when facing undead mobs you can forgo the typical &quot;Slower&quot; and grab another pet caster.<br>
<br>
Necromancers, thru to use of Feign Death, greatly increase the chances of pulling single spawns from multiple static spawns by &quot;Feign Death Pulling&quot;.  This helps to remove the need to a crowd controling class (thus making room for yet another pet caster) and the Necromancer has Screaming Terror (a short general purpose Mez but too low level for PoP), Deaths Silence (high level Undead only mez) and various Root spells (for &quot;parking&quot; a mob out of combat) to handle some of the crowd control requirements.<br>
<br>
Charm and Dire Charm can give a Necromancer a very powerful pet but they both come with downsides.  While using either of them the Necromancer can no longer do FD pulling and can no longer invis (either action will result in the charmed pet being set free) but both result in a much stronger pet then normally can be summoned.<br>
<br>
If the mob is just to powerful for the army of pets to tank then there are very few classes which can snare and hold a mobs hatred better then a Necromancer.  With Darkness in place we have some debuffs which cause enough taunt that even SKs gasp in disgust, making 'agro kiting' a very easy option.<br>
<br>
As for the pet agro debate, I have seen it work all kinds of different ways.  Sometimes it is the &quot;weakest&quot; pet, sometimes it is the second pet and sometimes with two or more pets you can engage in melee and not draw agro right away.  I am sure VI has some complex code at work behind the scences to keep &quot;pet armies&quot; from being used in raid type settings.  Really wish VI would undo the pet taunt nerf...<br>
<br>
